    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>STANLEY CUP FINALS GET BETTER RATINGS</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By RICHARD SANDOMIR</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Sandomir, Richard</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Game 6 of Stanley Cup finals produced 4.2 Neilsen rating for ABC, same as Game 5 (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Game 6 of the Stanley Cup finals Saturday produced a 4.2 Neilsen rating for ABC, the same as Game 5. The four Devils-Dallas games carried by ABC averaged a 3.7 rating, up from the 3.4 Fox posted for three games last year.</p>
        <p>For all 10 of its playoff games, ABC averaged a 2.5 rating, up from a 2.2 on Fox last year. ABC and ESPN are jointly spending $120 million a year for National Hockey League rights.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Game 6 of the Stanley Cup finals Saturday produced a 4.2 Neilsen rating for ABC, the same as Game 5. The four Devils-Dallas games carried by ABC averaged a 3.7 rating, up from the 3.4 Fox posted for three games last year.</p>
        <p>For all 10 of its playoff games, ABC averaged a 2.5 rating, up from a 2.2 on Fox last year. ABC and ESPN are jointly spending $120 million a year for National Hockey League rights.</p>
        <p>At NBC, Game 3 of the National Basketball Association finals on Sunday between the Los Angeles Lakers and Indiana Pacers generated a 10.7 rating, down 11.5 percent from a 12.1 for the comparable game last year between the Knicks and San Antonio.</p>
        <p>RICHARD SANDOMIR</p>
